Decorator pattern solves this by adding behavior dynamically at runtime.


Decorator
Attach additional responsibilities to an object dynamically. Decorators provide a flexible alternative to subclassing for extending functionality. The pattern has structural purpose and applies to objects.

When to use
to add responsibilities to individual objects dynamically and transparently, that is, without affecting other objects
for responsibilities that can be withdrawn
when extension by subclassing is impractical

=======================

Base Price = 1000
+ Discount
+ Tax
+ Service Fee

Each step adds behavior, not replaces it.

👉 That’s Decorator

🏗️ Design
1️⃣ Component
class Price {
public:
    virtual int getPrice() = 0;
    virtual ~Price() {}
};
2️⃣ Base Component
class BasePrice : public Price {
public:
    int getPrice() override {
        return 1000;
    }
};
3️⃣ Decorator Base
class PriceDecorator : public Price {
protected:
    Price* price;

public:
    PriceDecorator(Price* p) : price(p) {}
};
4️⃣ Concrete Decorators
Discount
class DiscountDecorator : public PriceDecorator {
public:
    DiscountDecorator(Price* p) : PriceDecorator(p) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() - 100;
    }
};
Tax
class TaxDecorator : public PriceDecorator {
public:
    TaxDecorator(Price* p) : PriceDecorator(p) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() + 50;
    }
};
Service Fee
class FeeDecorator : public PriceDecorator {
public:
    FeeDecorator(Price* p) : PriceDecorator(p) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() + 20;
    }
};
🚀 Usage (very important)
Price* price = new BasePrice();

price = new DiscountDecorator(price);
price = new TaxDecorator(price);
price = new FeeDecorator(price);

cout << price->getPrice();


==================

class BookingPrice {
public:
    virtual int getPrice() = 0;
    virtual ~BookingPrice() {}
};
Step 2 — Base Price
class BaseBookingPrice : public BookingPrice {
    int base;

public:
    BaseBookingPrice(int b) : base(b) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return base;
    }
};
Step 3 — Decorator Base
class BookingPriceDecorator : public BookingPrice {
protected:
    BookingPrice* price;

public:
    BookingPriceDecorator(BookingPrice* p) : price(p) {}
};
Step 4 — Now YOU think (important)

We need 3 decorators:

Coupon
Loyalty Discount
Tax

👉 Let’s build one together.

Coupon Decorator
class CouponDecorator : public BookingPriceDecorator {
    int couponValue;

public:
    CouponDecorator(BookingPrice* p, int c)
        : BookingPriceDecorator(p), couponValue(c) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() - couponValue;
    }
};

Loyalty Decorator
class LoyaltyDecorator : public BookingPriceDecorator {
    int loyaltyDiscount;

public:
    LoyaltyDecorator(BookingPrice* p, int d)
        : BookingPriceDecorator(p), loyaltyDiscount(d) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() - loyaltyDiscount;
    }
};
Tax Decorator
class TaxDecorator : public BookingPriceDecorator {
    int tax;

public:
    TaxDecorator(BookingPrice* p, int t)
        : BookingPriceDecorator(p), tax(t) {}

    int getPrice() override {
        return price->getPrice() + tax;
    }
};
Final Usage (very important)
int main() {
    BookingPrice* price = new BaseBookingPrice(1000);

    price = new CouponDecorator(price, 100);
    price = new LoyaltyDecorator(price, 50);
    price = new TaxDecorator(price, 80);

    cout << price->getPrice();
}